# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: capacitor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] In its simplest implementation, capacitive coupling is achieved by placing a capacitor between two nodes.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] Where analysis of many points in a circuit is carried out, the capacitance at each point and between points can be described in a matrix form.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] In analog circuits, a coupling capacitor is used to connect two circuits such that only the AC signal from the first circuit can pass through to the next while DC is blocked.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] This technique helps to isolate the DC bias settings of the two coupled circuits.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] Capacitive coupling is also known as *AC coupling* and the capacitor used for the purpose is also known as a *DC-blocking capacitor*.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] A coupling capacitor's ability to prevent a DC load from interfering with an AC source is particularly useful in Class A amplifier circuits by preventing a 0 volt input being passed to a transistor with additional resistor biasing; creating continuous amplification.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] Capacitive coupling decreases the low frequency gain of a system containing capacitively coupled units.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] Each coupling capacitor along with the input electrical impedance of the next stage forms a high-pass filter and the sequence of filters results in a cumulative filter with a cutoff frequency that may be higher than those of each individual filter.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] Coupling capacitors can also introduce nonlinear distortion at low frequencies.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] This is not an issue at high frequencies because the voltage across the capacitor stays very close to zero.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] However, if a signal passing through the coupling capacitance has a frequency that is low relative to the RC cutoff frequency, voltages can develop across the capacitor, which for some capacitor types results in changes of capacitance, leading to distortion.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] This is avoided by choosing capacitor types that have low *voltage coefficient*, and by using large values that put the cutoff frequency far lower than the frequencies of the signal.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] AC coupling is also widely used in digital circuits to transmit digital signals with a zero DC component, known as DC-balanced signals.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] DC-balanced waveforms are useful in communications systems, since they can be used over AC-coupled electrical connections to avoid voltage imbalance problems and charge accumulation between connected systems or components.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] For this reason, most modern line codes are designed to produce DC-balanced waveforms.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] The most common classes of DC-balanced line codes are constant-weight codes and paired-disparity codes.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] A gimmick loop is a simple type of capacitive coupler: two closely spaced strands of wire.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] It provides capacitive coupling of a few picofarads between two nodes.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] Capacitive coupling is often unintended, such as the capacitance between two wires or PCB traces that are next to each other.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] One signal may capacitively couple with another and cause what appears to be noise.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] To reduce coupling, wires or traces are often separated as much as possible, or ground lines or ground planes are run in between signals that might affect each other, so that the lines capacitively couple to ground rather than each other.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] Prototypes of high-frequency (tens of megahertz) or high-gain analog circuits often use circuits that are built over a ground plane to control unwanted coupling.
[src:capacitor/ac-coupling] If a high-gain amplifier's output capacitively couples to its input it may become an electronic oscillator.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:capacitor/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] An **accelerometer** is a device that measures the proper acceleration of an object.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is the acceleration (the rate of change of velocity) of the object relative to an observer who is in free fall (that is, relative to an inertial frame of reference).
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is different from coordinate acceleration, which is acceleration with respect to a given coordinate system, which may or may not be accelerating.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] For example, an accelerometer at rest on the surface of the Earth will measure an acceleration due to Earth's gravity straight upwards of about *g* ≈ 9.81 m/s2.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] By contrast, an accelerometer that is in free fall will measure zero acceleration.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Highly sensitive accelerometers are used in inertial navigation systems for aircraft and missiles.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] In unmanned aerial vehicles, accelerometers help to stabilize flight.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Micromachined micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) accelerometers are used in handheld electronic devices such as smartphones, cameras and video-game controllers to detect movement and orientation of these devices.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Vibration in industrial machinery is monitored by accelerometers.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Seismometers are sensitive accelerometers for monitoring ground movement such as earthquakes.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] When two or more accelerometers are coordinated with one another, they can measure differences in proper acceleration, particularly gravity, over their separation in space—that is, the gradient of the gravitational field.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Gravity gradiometry is useful because absolute gravity is a weak effect and depends on the local density of the Earth, which is quite variable.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] A single-axis accelerometer measures acceleration along a specified axis.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] A multi-axis accelerometer detects both the magnitude and the direction of the proper acceleration, as a vector quantity, and is usually implemented as several single-axis accelerometers oriented along different axes.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] An accelerometer measures proper acceleration, which is the acceleration it experiences relative to freefall and is the acceleration felt by people and objects.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Put another way, at any point in spacetime the equivalence principle guarantees the existence of a local inertial frame, and an accelerometer measures the acceleration relative to that frame.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Such accelerations are popularly denoted g-force; i.e., in comparison to standard gravity.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] An accelerometer at rest relative to the Earth's surface will indicate approximately 1 g *upwards* because the Earth's surface exerts a normal force upwards relative to the local inertial frame (the frame of a freely falling object near the surface).
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] To obtain the acceleration due to motion with respect to the Earth, this "gravity offset" must be subtracted and corrections made for effects caused by the Earth's rotation relative to the inertial frame.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The reason for the appearance of a gravitational offset is Einstein's equivalence principle, which states that the effects of gravity on an object are indistinguishable from acceleration.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] When held fixed in a gravitational field by, for example, applying a ground reaction force or an equivalent upward thrust, the reference frame for an accelerometer (its own casing) accelerates upwards with respect to a free-falling reference frame.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] For similar reasons, an accelerometer will read *zero* during any type of free fall.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] This includes use in a coasting spaceship in deep space far from any mass, a spaceship orbiting the Earth, an airplane in a parabolic "zero-g" arc, or any free-fall in a vacuum.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Another example is free-fall at a sufficiently high altitude that atmospheric effects can be neglected.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] However, this does not include a (non-free) fall in which air resistance produces drag forces that reduce the acceleration until constant terminal velocity is reached.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] At terminal velocity, the accelerometer will indicate 1 g acceleration upwards.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] For the same reason a skydiver, upon reaching terminal velocity, does not feel as though he or she were in "free-fall", but rather experiences a feeling similar to being supported (at 1 g) on a "bed" of uprushing air.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Acceleration is quantified in the SI unit metres per second per second (m/s2), in the cgs unit gal (Gal), or popularly in terms of standard gravity (*g*).
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] For the practical purpose of finding the acceleration of objects with respect to the Earth, such as for use in an inertial navigation system, a knowledge of local gravity is required.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] This can be obtained either by calibrating the device at rest, or from a known model of gravity at the approximate current position.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] A basic mechanical accelerometer is a damped proof mass on a spring.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] When the accelerometer experiences an acceleration, Newton's third law causes the spring's compression (or extension) to adjust to exert an equivalent force on the mass to counteract the acceleration.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Since the spring's force scales linearly with the length change (according to Hooke's law) and because the spring constant and mass are known constants, a measurement of the spring's compression (or extension) is also a measurement of acceleration.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The system is damped to prevent oscillations of the mass and spring interfering with measurements.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] However, the damping causes accelerometers to have a frequency response.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Many animals have sensory organs to detect acceleration, especially gravity.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] In these, the proof mass is usually one or more crystals of calcium carbonate otoliths (Latin for "ear stone") or statoconia, acting against a bed of hairs connected to neurons.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The hairs form the springs, with the neurons as sensors.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Many vertebrates, including humans, have these structures in their inner ears.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Most invertebrates have similar organs, but not as part of their hearing organs.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Mechanical accelerometers are often designed so that an electronic circuit senses a small amount of motion, then pushes on the proof mass with some type of linear motor to keep the proof mass from moving far.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The motor might be an electromagnet or in very small accelerometers, electrostatic.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Since the circuit's electronic behavior can be carefully designed, and the proof mass does not move far, these designs can be very stable (i.e. they do not oscillate), very linear with a controlled frequency response.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] In mechanical accelerometers, measurement is often electrical, piezoelectric, piezoresistive or capacitive.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers use piezoceramic sensors (e.g. lead zirconate titanate) or single crystals (e.g. quartz, tourmaline).
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] They are unmatched in high frequency measurements, low packaged weight, and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Piezoresistive accelerometers resist shock (very high accelerations) better.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Capacitive accelerometers typically use a silicon micro-machined sensing element.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Modern mechanical accelerometers are often small *micro-electro-mechanical systems* (MEMS), and are often very simple MEMS devices, consisting of little more than a cantilever beam with a proof mass (also known as *seismic mass*).
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Damping results from the residual gas sealed in the device.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] As long as the Q-factor is not too low, damping does not result in a lower sensitivity.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Under the influence of external accelerations, the proof mass deflects from its neutral position.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] This deflection is measured in an analog or digital manner.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Most commonly, the capacitance between a set of fixed beams and a set of beams attached to the proof mass is measured.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] This method is simple, reliable, and inexpensive.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Integrating piezoresistors in the springs to detect spring deformation, and thus deflection, is a good alternative, although a few more process steps are needed during the fabrication sequence.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] For very high sensitivities quantum tunnelling is also used; this requires a dedicated process making it very expensive.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Optical measurement has been demonstrated in laboratory devices.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Another MEMS-based accelerometer is a thermal (or convective) accelerometer.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] It contains a small heater in a very small dome.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] This heats the air or other fluid inside the dome.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The thermal bubble acts as the proof mass.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] An accompanying temperature sensor (like a thermistor; or thermopile) in the dome measures the temperature in one location of the dome.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] This measures the location of the heated bubble within the dome.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] When the dome is accelerated, the colder, higher density fluid pushes the heated bubble.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The temperature measurement is interpreted as acceleration.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Gravity acting on the fluid provides the spring.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Since the proof mass is very lightweight gas, and not held by a beam or lever, thermal accelerometers can survive high shocks.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Another variation uses a wire to both heat the gas and detect the change in temperature.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The change of temperature changes the resistance of the wire.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] A two dimensional accelerometer can be economically constructed with one dome, one bubble and two measurement devices.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Most micromechanical accelerometers operate *in-plane*, that is, they are designed to be sensitive only to a direction in the plane of the die.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] By integrating two devices perpendicularly on a single die a two-axis accelerometer can be made.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] By adding another *out-of-plane* device, three axes can be measured.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Such a combination may have much lower misalignment error than three discrete models combined after packaging.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Micromechanical accelerometers are available in a wide variety of measuring ranges, reaching up to thousands of *g*'s.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The designer must compromise between sensitivity and the maximum acceleration that can be measured.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vehicle acceleration.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vibration on cars, machines, buildings, process control systems and safety installations.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] They can also be used to measure seismic activity, inclination, machine vibration, dynamic distance and speed with or without the influence of gravity.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Applications for accelerometers that measure gravity, wherein an accelerometer is specifically configured for use in gravimetry, are called gravimeters.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also increasingly used in the biological sciences.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] High frequency recordings of bi-axial or tri-axial acceleration allows the discrimination of behavioral patterns while animals are out of sight.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] For example, accelerometers have been used to study flight energy expenditure of Harris's Hawk (*Parabuteo unicinctus*).
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Researchers are also using smartphone accelerometers to collect and extract mechano-biological descriptors of resistance exercise.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Increasingly, researchers are deploying accelerometers with additional technology, such as cameras or microphones, to better understand animal behaviour in the wild (for example, hunting behaviour of Canada lynx).
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also used for machinery health monitoring to report the vibration and its changes in time of shafts at the bearings of rotating equipment such as turbines, pumps, fans, rollers, compressors, or bearing fault which, if not attended to promptly, can lead to costly repairs.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometer vibration data allows the user to monitor machines and detect these faults before the rotating equipment fails completely.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers are widely used in structural health monitoring (SHM) of buildings, bridges and other civil infrastructure to record the dynamic response under ambient and forced loads (e.g., wind, traffic, machinery and earthquakes).
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] From these vibration records, engineers estimate modal properties—natural frequencies, damping ratios and mode shapes—often using operational modal analysis (OMA) techniques for in-service structures.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] These parameters are trended over time for condition assessment and model updating.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] In seismic regions, arrays of accelerometers installed in buildings and other structures provide strong-motion data for rapid post-event assessments and long-term performance studies.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Geological Survey's National Strong-Motion Project (NSMP) operates structural arrays and distributes building and structural records via the Center for Engineering Strong Motion Data (CESMD).
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Instrumentation and data-quality practices for building vibration measurements are guided by international standards.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] ISO 4866 provides principles for measuring the vibration of fixed structures and evaluating vibration effects based on structural response, while ISO 10137 gives serviceability recommendations for buildings and walkways with respect to human perception, contents and the structure itself.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Choice of accelerometer technology depends on frequency range and amplitude.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers are common for higher-frequency, higher-amplitude measurements, whereas low-noise MEMS accelerometers have become attractive for low-frequency building and bridge monitoring and for dense or wireless deployments due to cost and power advantages.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Recent evaluations and developments show that appropriately selected MEMS devices can identify modal parameters with acceptable accuracy for SHM and have been integrated into high-sensitivity wireless nodes.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Networked and wireless smart-sensor approaches allow distributed monitoring at scale.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Reviews document the shift from wired to wireless SHM systems and the maturation of wireless smart-sensor networks for tasks such as ambient-vibration modal identification and continuous trending.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers are often fused with other sensors to improve displacement and drift estimation, especially for large or flexible structures.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] GNSS provides quasi-static and very-low-frequency motion that complements accelerometer-based dynamics; recent studies report accurate dynamic displacement retrieval using high-rate or multi-GNSS solutions combined with accelerometers.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Beyond permanently instrumented assets, indirect and crowdsourced approaches using smartphone accelerometers have been explored, particularly for bridges.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Research has shown that modal frequencies—and in some cases spatial vibration characteristics—can be estimated from accelerometer data collected by vehicles crossing bridges, offering a complementary, low-cost screening tool for large inventories.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Related work has also evaluated smartphone-based ambient vibration monitoring of buildings.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Long-term case studies illustrate large-scale deployments.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Hong Kong's Wind and Structural Health Monitoring System (WASHMS) has instrumented the Tsing Ma Bridge since 1997; subsequent publications report decades of monitoring for load and response in service.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Scotland's Queensferry Crossing was equipped with a comprehensive SHM system including thousands of sensors, and Sydney Harbour Bridge has been reported as instrumented with thousands of sensors for real-time monitoring.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] SHM data are used for continuous condition tracking, event-triggered assessments (e.g., after earthquakes), and to support asset management decisions.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] In bridge engineering, guidance from transportation agencies describes how field data—including accelerometer measurements—can be integrated with inspection and nondestructive evaluation to improve load-rating reliability and maintenance planning.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Zoll's AED Plus uses CPR-D•padz which contain an accelerometer to measure the depth of CPR chest compressions.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Within the last several years, several companies have produced and marketed sports watches for runners that include footpods, containing accelerometers to help determine the speed and distance for the runner wearing the unit.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] In Belgium, accelerometer-based step counters are promoted by the government to encourage people to walk a few thousand steps each day.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Herman Digital Trainer uses accelerometers to measure strike force in physical training.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] It has been suggested to build football helmets with accelerometers in order to measure the impact of head collisions.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The US Army Research Laboratory developed the Three-Axis Acceleration Switch which has been suggested for this application.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers have been used to calculate gait parameters, such as stance and swing phase.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] This kind of sensor can be used to measure or monitor people.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] An inertial navigation system is a navigation aid that uses a computer and motion sensors (accelerometers) to continuously calculate via dead reckoning the position, orientation, and velocity (direction and speed of movement) of a moving object without the need for external references.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Other terms used to refer to inertial navigation systems or closely related devices include inertial guidance system, inertial reference platform, and many other variations.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] An accelerometer alone is unsuitable to determine changes in altitude over distances where the vertical decrease of gravity is significant, such as for aircraft and rockets.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] In the presence of a gravitational gradient, the calibration and data reduction process is numerically unstable.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used to detect apogee in both professional and in amateur rocketry.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also being used in Intelligent Compaction rollers.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used alongside gyroscopes in inertial navigation systems.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] One of the most common uses for MEMS accelerometers is in airbag deployment systems for modern automobiles.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] In this case, the accelerometers are used to detect the rapid negative acceleration of the vehicle to determine when a collision has occurred and the severity of the collision.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Another common automotive use is in electronic stability control systems, which use a lateral accelerometer to measure cornering forces.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The widespread use of accelerometers in the automotive industry has pushed their cost down dramatically.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Another automotive application is the monitoring of noise, vibration, and harshness (NVH), conditions that cause discomfort for drivers and passengers and may also be indicators of mechanical faults.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Tilting trains use accelerometers and gyroscopes to calculate the required tilt.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Modern electronic accelerometers are used in remote sensing devices intended for the monitoring of active volcanoes to detect the motion of magma.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers are increasingly being incorporated into personal electronic devices to detect the orientation of the device, for example, a display screen.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] A *free-fall sensor* (FFS) is an accelerometer used to detect if a system has been dropped and is falling.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] It can then apply safety measures such as parking the head of a hard disk to prevent a head crash and resulting data loss upon impact.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] This device is included in the many common computer and consumer electronic products that are produced by a variety of manufacturers.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] It is also used in some data loggers to monitor handling operations for shipping containers.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The length of time in free fall is used to calculate the height of drop and to estimate the shock to the package.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Some smartphones, digital audio players and personal digital assistants contain accelerometers for user interface control; often the accelerometer is used to present landscape or portrait views of the device's screen, based on the way the device is being held.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Apple has included an accelerometer in every generation of iPhone, iPad, and iPod touch, as well as in every iPod nano since the 4th generation.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Along with orientation view adjustment, accelerometers in mobile devices can also be used as pedometers, in conjunction with specialized applications.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Automatic Collision Notification (ACN) systems also use accelerometers in a system to call for help in event of a vehicle crash.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Prominent ACN systems include OnStar AACN service, Ford Link's 911 Assist, Toyota's Safety Connect, Lexus Link, or BMW Assist.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Many accelerometer-equipped smartphones also have ACN software available for download.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] ACN systems are activated by detecting crash-strength accelerations.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used in vehicle Electronic stability control systems to measure the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] A computer compares the vehicle's actual movement to the driver's steering and throttle input.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The stability control computer can selectively brake individual wheels and/or reduce engine power to minimize the difference between driver input and the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] This can help prevent the vehicle from spinning or rolling over.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Some pedometers use an accelerometer to more accurately measure the number of steps taken and distance traveled than a mechanical sensor can provide.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Nintendo's Wii video game console uses a controller called a Wii Remote that contains a three-axis accelerometer and was designed primarily for motion input.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Users also have the option of buying an additional motion-sensitive attachment, the Nunchuk, so that motion input could be recorded from both of the user's hands independently.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Is also used on the Nintendo 3DS system.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Sleep phase alarm clocks use accelerometric sensors to detect movement of a sleeper, so that it can wake the person when he/she is not in REM phase, in order to awaken the person more easily.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] A microphone or eardrum is a membrane that responds to oscillations in air pressure.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] These oscillations cause acceleration, so accelerometers can be used to record sound.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] A 2012 study found that voices can be detected in 93% of typical daily situations by accelerometers like those in smartphones fixed to the sternum.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Conversely, carefully designed sounds can cause accelerometers to report false data.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] One study tested 20 models of (MEMS) smartphone accelerometers and found that a majority were susceptible to this attack.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] A number of 21st-century devices use accelerometers to align the screen depending on the direction the device is held (e.g., switching between portrait and landscape modes).
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Such devices include many tablet PCs and some smartphones and digital cameras.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The Amida Simputer, a handheld Linux device launched in 2004, was the first commercial handheld to have a built-in accelerometer.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] It incorporated many gesture-based interactions using this accelerometer, including page-turning, zoom-in and zoom-out of images, change of portrait to landscape mode, and many simple gesture-based games.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] As of January 2009, almost all new mobile phones and digital cameras contain at least a tilt sensor and sometimes an accelerometer for the purpose of auto image rotation, motion-sensitive mini-games, and correcting shake when taking photographs.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Camcorders use accelerometers for image stabilization, either by moving optical elements to adjust the light path to the sensor to cancel out unintended motions or digitally shifting the image to smooth out detected motion.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Some stills cameras use accelerometers for anti-blur capturing.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The camera holds off capturing the image when the camera is moving.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] When the camera is still (if only for a millisecond, as could be the case for vibration), the image is captured.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] An example of the application of this technology is the Glogger VS2, a phone application which runs on Symbian based phones with accelerometers such as the Nokia N96.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Some digital cameras contain accelerometers to determine the orientation of the photo being taken and also for rotating the current picture when viewing.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Many laptops feature an accelerometer which is used to detect drops.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] If a drop is detected, the heads of the hard disk are parked to avoid data loss and possible head or disk damage by the ensuing shock.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] A gravimeter, or gravitometer, is an instrument used in gravimetry for measuring the local gravitational field.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] A gravimeter is a type of accelerometer, except that accelerometers are susceptible to all vibrations including noise, that cause oscillatory accelerations.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] This is counteracted in the gravimeter by integral vibration isolation and signal processing.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Though the essential principle of design is the same as in accelerometers, gravimeters are typically designed to be much more sensitive than accelerometers in order to measure very tiny changes within the Earth's gravity, of 1 *g*.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] In contrast, other accelerometers are often designed to measure 1000 *g* or more, and many perform multi-axial measurements.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] The constraints on temporal resolution are usually less for gravimeters, so that resolution can be increased by processing the output with a longer "time constant".
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] If done without a user's knowledge or consent, this is referred to as an inference attack.
[src:capacitor/accelerometer] Additionally, millions of smartphones could be vulnerable to software cracking via accelerometers.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] An **acorn tube**, or **acorn valve**, is any member of a family of VHF/UHF vacuum tubes starting just before World War II.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] They were named after their resemblance to the acorn, specifically due to the glass cap at one end of the tube that looked similar to the cap on an acorn.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] The acorn tubes found widespread use in radios and radar systems.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] High-frequency performance is limited by (1) parasitic lead inductance and capacitance and skin effect, and (2) electron transit time (the time required to travel from cathode to anode).
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] Transit time effects are complicated, but one simple effect is the phase margin; another one is input conductance, also known as grid loading.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] At extremely high frequencies, electrons arriving at the grid may become out of phase with those departing towards the anode.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] This imbalance of charge causes the grid to exhibit a reactance that is much less than its low-frequency "open circuit" characteristic.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] Acorn- as well as Lighthouse tubes and Nuvistors attempt to minimize this effect by arranging cathode, grid(s) and anode as closely spaced together as possible.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] The original range included about half a dozen tubes, designed to work in the VHF range.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] The 954 and 956 types are sharp and remote cut-off pentodes, respectively, all with indirect 6.3 V, 150 mA heaters.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] Types 957, 958 and 959 are for portable equipment and have 1.25 V NiCd battery heaters.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] The 957 is a medium-μ signal triode, the 958 is a transmitting triode with dual, paralleled filaments for increased emission, and the 959 is a sharp cut-off pentode like the 954.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] The 957 and 959 draw 50 mA heater current, the 958 twice as much.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] In 1942, the 958A with tightened emission specifications was introduced after it turned out that 958s with excessively high emission kept working after the filament power was turned off, the filament still sufficiently heating on the anode current alone.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] After the introduction of the miniature 7-pin base, the 954, 955 and 956 were made available with this base as 9001, 9002 and 9003.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] Larger, higher-power types such as the 316A, 368A, 388A, and 703A triodes and the 713A and 717A pentodes were referred to as *Doorknob* tubes.
[src:capacitor/acorn-tube] The introduction of the EF50 was the first serious competition for the acorn design, and replaced the acorns in many roles, especially post-war when millions of surplus EF50s were dumped on the market.
[src:capacitor/additron-tube] The **Additron** was an electron tube designed by Dr.
[src:capacitor/additron-tube] Josef Kates, circa 1950, to replace the several individual electron tubes and support components required to perform the function of a single bit digital full adder.
[src:capacitor/additron-tube] The Additron neither went into production at the Canadian Rogers Vacuum Tube Company, where the prototypes were built, nor was it used in the UTEC machine.
[src:capacitor/additron-tube] It did make a widely publicized appearance at the 1950 Canadian National Exhibition operating an electronic game of Tic-Tac-Toe, dubbed *Bertie the Brain*, to show the marvels of electronic computing.
[src:capacitor/additron-tube] The tube was registered with the Radio Television Manufacturing Association on 20 March 1951 as type 6047.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogels are produced by extracting the liquid component of a gel through supercritical drying or freeze-drying.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] This allows the liquid to be slowly dried off without causing the solid matrix in the gel to collapse from capillary action, as would happen with conventional evaporation.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The first aerogels were produced from silica gels.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Kistler's later work involved aerogels based on alumina, chromia, and tin dioxide.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Carbon aerogels were first developed in the late 1980s.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The first documented example of an aerogel was created by Samuel Stephens Kistler in 1931, as a result of a bet with Charles Learned over who could replace the liquid in "jellies" with gas without causing shrinkage.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Despite the name, aerogels are solid, rigid, and dry materials that do not resemble a gel in their physical properties: the name is because they are made *from* gels.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Pressing softly on an aerogel typically does not leave even a minor mark; pressing more firmly will leave a permanent depression.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Pressing extremely firmly will cause a breakdown in the sparse structure causing it to shatter like glass (a property known as *friability*), although more modern variations do not suffer from this.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Even though it is prone to shattering, it is very strong structurally.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Its impressive load-bearing abilities are due to the dendritic microstructure in which spherical particles of average size 2–5 nm are fused together into clusters.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] These clusters form a three-dimensional highly porous structure of almost fractal chains, with pores just under 100 nm.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The average size and density of the pores can be controlled during the manufacturing process.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] An aerogel material can range from 50% to 99.98% air by volume, but in practice most aerogels exhibit somewhere between 90 and 99.8% porosity.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogels have a porous solid network that contains air pockets, with the air pockets taking up the majority of space within the material.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogels are good thermal insulators because they almost nullify two of the three methods of heat transfer – conduction (they are mostly composed of insulating gas) and convection (the microstructure prevents net gas movement).
[src:capacitor/aerogel] They are good conductive insulators because they are composed almost entirely of gases, which are very poor heat conductors.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] (Silica aerogel is an especially good insulator because silica is also a poor conductor of heat; a metallic or carbon aerogel, on the other hand, would be less effective.) They are good convective inhibitors because air cannot circulate through the lattice.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogels are poor radiative insulators because infrared radiation (which transfers heat) passes through them.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Owing to its hygroscopic nature, aerogel feels dry and acts as a strong desiccant.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] People handling aerogel for extended periods should wear gloves to prevent the appearance of dry brittle spots on their skin.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The slight color it does have is due to Rayleigh scattering of the shorter wavelengths of visible light by the nano-sized dendritic structure.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] This causes it to appear smoky blue against dark backgrounds and yellowish against bright backgrounds.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogels by themselves are hydrophilic, and if they absorb moisture they usually suffer a structural change, such as contraction, and deteriorate, but degradation can be prevented by making them hydrophobic, via a chemical treatment.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogels with hydrophobic interiors are less susceptible to degradation than aerogels with only an outer hydrophobic layer, especially if a crack penetrates the surface.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogel structure results from a sol-gel polymerization, which is when monomers (simple molecules) react with other monomers to form a sol or a substance that consists of bonded, cross-linked macromolecules with deposits of liquid solution among them.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] When the material is critically heated, the liquid evaporates and the bonded, cross-linked macromolecule frame is left behind.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The result of the polymerization and critical heating is the creation of a material that has a porous strong structure classified as aerogel.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Variations in synthesis can alter the surface area and pore size of the aerogel.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The smaller the pore size the more susceptible the aerogel is to fracture.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] There are several ways to determine the porosity of aerogel: the three main methods are gas adsorption, mercury porosimetry, and scattering method.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] In gas adsorption, nitrogen at its boiling point is adsorbed into the aerogel sample.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The gas being adsorbed is dependent on the size of the pores within the sample and on the partial pressure of the gas relative to its saturation pressure.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The volume of the gas adsorbed is measured by using the Brunauer, Emmit and Teller formula (BET), which gives the specific surface area of the sample.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] At high partial pressure in the adsorption/desorption the Kelvin equation gives the pore size distribution of the sample.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] In mercury porosimetry, the mercury is forced into the aerogel porous system to determine the pores' size, but this method is highly inefficient since the solid frame of aerogel will collapse from the high compressive force.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The scattering method involves the angle-dependent deflection of radiation within the aerogel sample.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The sample can be solid particles or pores.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The radiation goes into the material and determines the fractal geometry of the aerogel pore network.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The best radiation wavelengths to use are X-rays and neutrons.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The high porosity and surface area of silica aerogels allow them to be used in a variety of environmental filtration applications.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogels may have a thermal conductivity smaller than that of the gas they contain.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] This is caused by the Knudsen effect, a reduction of thermal conductivity in gases when the size of the cavity encompassing the gas becomes comparable to the mean free path.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Effectively, the cavity restricts the movement of the gas particles, decreasing the thermal conductivity in addition to eliminating convection.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] For example, thermal conductivity of air is about 25 mW·m−1·K−1 at standard temperature and pressure (STP) and in a large container, but decreases to about 5 mW·m−1·K−1 in a pore 30 nanometers in diameter.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogel contains particles that are 2–5 nm in diameter.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] After the process of creating aerogel, it will contain a large amount of hydroxyl groups on the surface.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The hydroxyl groups can cause a strong reaction when the aerogel is placed in water, causing it to dissolve in the water.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] One way to waterproof the hydrophilic aerogel is by soaking the aerogel with some chemical base that will replace the surface hydroxyl groups (–OH) with non-polar groups (–O*R*), a process which is most effective when *R* is an aliphatic group.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The preparation of silica aerogels typically involves three distinct steps: the sol-gel transition (gelation), the network perfection (aging), and the gel-aerogel transition (drying).
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Silica aerogels are typically synthesized by using a sol-gel process.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The first step of the sol-gel process is the creation of a colloidal suspension of solid particles known as a "sol".
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The precursors are a liquid alcohol such as ethanol which is mixed with a silicon alkoxide, such as tetramethoxysilane (TMOS), tetraethoxysilane (TEOS), and polyethoxydisiloxane (PEDS) (earlier work used sodium silicates).
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The solution of silica is mixed with a catalyst and allowed to gel during a hydrolysis reaction which forms particles of silicon dioxide.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The oxide suspension begins to undergo condensation reactions which result in the creation of metal oxide bridges (either M–O–M, "oxo" bridges, or M–OH–M, "ol" bridges) linking the dispersed colloidal particles.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] These reactions generally have moderately slow reaction rates, and as a result either acidic or basic catalysts are used to improve the processing speed.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Basic catalysts tend to produce more transparent aerogels and minimize the shrinkage during the drying process and also strengthen it to prevent pore collapse during drying.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] For some materials, the transition from a colloidal dispersion into a gel happens without the addition of crosslinking materials.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] For others, crosslinking materials are added to the dispersion to promote the strong interaction of the solid particles in order to form the gel.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The gelation time depends heavily on a variety of factors such as the chemical composition of the precursor solution, the concentration of the precursor materials and additives, the processing temperature, and the pH.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Many materials may require additional curing after gelation (i.e., network perfection) in order to strengthen the aerogel network.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Once the gelation is completed, the liquid surrounding the silica network is carefully removed and replaced with air, while keeping the aerogel intact.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] It is crucial that the gel is dried in such a way as to minimize the surface tension within the pores of the solid network.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] This is typically accomplished through supercritical fluid extraction using supercritical carbon dioxide (scCO2) or freeze-drying.This section briefly describes and compares the processing strategies of supercritical drying and freeze-drying.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Gels where the liquid is allowed to evaporate at a natural rate are known as xerogels (i. e. are not aerogels).
[src:capacitor/aerogel] As the liquid evaporates in such manner, forces caused by surface tensions of the liquid-solid interfaces are enough to destroy the fragile gel network.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] As a result, xerogels cannot achieve the high porosities and instead peak at lower porosities and exhibit large amounts of shrinkage after drying.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] To avoid the collapse of fibers during slow solvent evaporation and reduce surface tensions of the liquid-solid interfaces, aerogels can be formed by lyophilization (freeze-drying).
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Depending on the concentration of the fibers and the temperature to freeze the material, the properties such as porosity of the final aerogel will be affected.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] In 1931, to develop the first aerogels, Kistler used a process known as supercritical drying which avoids a direct phase change.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] By increasing the temperature and pressure he forced the liquid into a supercritical fluid state where by dropping the pressure he could instantly gasify and remove the liquid inside the aerogel, avoiding damage to the delicate three-dimensional network.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] While this can be done with ethanol, the high temperatures and pressures lead to dangerous processing conditions.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] A safer, lower temperature and pressure method involves a solvent exchange.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] This is typically done by exchanging the initial aqueous pore liquid for a CO2-miscible liquid such as ethanol or acetone, then onto liquid carbon dioxide, and then bringing the carbon dioxide above its critical point.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] A variant on this process involves the direct injection of supercritical carbon dioxide into the pressure vessel containing the aerogel.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The result of either process exchanges the initial liquid from the gel with carbon dioxide, without allowing the gel structure to collapse or lose volume.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] To dry the gel, while preserving the highly porous network of an aerogel, supercritical drying employs the use of the liquid-gas transition that occurs beyond the critical point of a substance.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] By using this liquid-gas transition that avoids crossing the liquid-gas phase boundary, the surface tension that would arise within the pores due to the evaporation of a liquid is eliminated, thereby preventing the collapse of the pores.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Through heating and pressurization, the liquid solvent reaches its critical point, at which point the liquid and gas phases become indistinguishable.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Past this point, the supercritical fluid is converted into the gaseous phase upon an isothermal de-pressurization.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] This process results in a phase change without crossing the liquid-gas phase boundary.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] This method is proven to be excellent at preserving the highly porous nature of the solid network without significant shrinkage or cracking.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] While other fluids have been reported for the creation of supercritically dried aerogels, scCO2 is the most common substance with a relatively mild supercritical point at 31 °C and 7.4 MPa.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] CO2 is also relatively non-toxic, non-flammable, inert, and cost-effective when compared to other fluids, such as methanol or ethanol.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] While being a highly effective method for producing aerogels, supercritical drying takes several days, requires specialized equipment, and presents significant safety hazards due to its high-pressure operation.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Freeze-drying, also known as freeze-casting or ice-templating, offers an alternative to the high temperature and high-pressure requirements of supercritical drying.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Additionally, freeze-drying offers more control of the solid structure development by controlling the ice crystal growth during freezing.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] In this method, a colloidal dispersion of the aerogel precursors is frozen, with the liquid component freezing into different morphologies depending on a variety of factors such as the precursor concentration, type of liquid, temperature of freezing, and freezing container.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] As this liquid freezes, the solid precursor molecules are forced into the spaces between the growing crystals.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Once completely frozen, the frozen liquid is sublimed into a gas through lyophilization, which removes much of the capillary forces, as was observed in supercritical drying.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Though typically classified as a "cryogel", aerogels produced through freeze-drying often experience some shrinkage and cracking while also producing a non-homogenous aerogel framework.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] This often leads to freeze-drying being used for the creation of aerogel powders or as a framework for composite aerogels.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Resorcinol–formaldehyde aerogel (RF aerogel) is made in a way similar to production of silica aerogel.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] A carbon aerogel can then be made from this resorcinol–formaldehyde aerogel by pyrolysis in an inert gas atmosphere, leaving a matrix of carbon.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The resulting carbon aerogel may be used to produce solid shapes, powders, or composite paper.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Additives have been successful in enhancing certain properties of the aerogel for the use of specific applications.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogel composites have been made using a variety of continuous and discontinuous reinforcements.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The high aspect ratio of fibers such as fiberglass have been used to reinforce aerogel composites with significantly improved mechanical properties.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Silica aerogels are the most common type of aerogel, and the primary type in use or study.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] It is silica-based and can be derived from silica gel or by a modified Stober process.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Nicknames include *frozen smoke*, *solid smoke*, *solid air*, *solid cloud*, and *blue smoke*, owing to its translucent nature and the way light scatters in the material.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The lowest-density silica nanofoam weighs 1,000 g/m3, which is the evacuated version of the record-aerogel of 1,900 g/m3.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The density of air is 1,200 g/m3 (at 20 °C and 1 atm).
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The silica solidifies into three-dimensional, intertwined clusters that make up only 3% of the volume.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Conduction through the solid is therefore very low.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The remaining 97% of the volume is composed of air in extremely small nanopores.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The air has little room to move, inhibiting both convection and gas-phase conduction.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Silica aerogel also has a high optical transmission of ~99% and a low refractive index of ~1.05.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] It is very robust with respect to high power input beam in continuous wave regime and does not show any boiling or melting phenomena.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] This property permits to study high intensity nonlinear waves in the presence of disorder in regimes typically unaccessible by liquid materials, making it promising material for nonlinear optics.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] This aerogel has remarkable thermal insulative properties, although its thermal conductivity depends on formulation, density, pressure and measurement method.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Until 2011, silica aerogel held 15 entries in *Guinness World Records* for material properties, including best insulator and lowest-density solid, though it was ousted from the latter title by the even lighter materials aerographite in 2012 and then aerographene in 2013.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Carbon aerogels are composed of particles with sizes in the nanometer range, covalently bonded together.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] They have very high porosity (over 50%, with pore diameter under 100 nm) and surface areas ranging between 400 and 1,000 m2/g.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] They are often manufactured as composite paper: non-woven paper made of carbon fibers, impregnated with resorcinol–formaldehyde aerogel, and pyrolyzed.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Depending on the density, carbon aerogels may be electrically conductive, making composite aerogel paper useful for electrodes in capacitors or deionization electrodes.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Due to their extremely high surface area, carbon aerogels are used to create supercapacitors, with values ranging up to thousands of farads based on a capacitance density of 104 F/g and 77 F/cm3.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Carbon aerogels are also extremely "black" in the infrared spectrum, reflecting only 0.3% of radiation between 250 nm and 14.3 μm, making them efficient for solar energy collectors.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] The term "aerogel" to describe airy masses of carbon nanotubes produced through certain chemical vapor deposition techniques is incorrect.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Such materials can be spun into fibers with strength greater than Kevlar, and unique electrical properties.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] These materials are not aerogels, however, since they do not have a monolithic internal structure and do not have the regular pore structure characteristic of aerogels.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Metal oxide aerogels are used as catalysts in various chemical reactions/transformations or as precursors for other materials.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogels made with aluminium oxide are known as alumina aerogels.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] These aerogels are used as catalysts, especially when "doped" with a metal other than aluminium.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Nickel–alumina aerogel is the most common combination.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Alumina aerogels are also being considered by NASA for capturing hypervelocity particles; a formulation doped with gadolinium and terbium could fluoresce at the particle impact site, with the amount of fluorescence dependent on impact energy.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] One of the most notable differences between silica aerogels and metal oxide aerogel is that metal oxide aerogels are often variedly colored.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Organic polymers can be used to create aerogels.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Cellulose from plants can be used to create a flexible aerogel.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] GraPhage13 is the first graphene-based aerogel assembled using graphene oxide and the M13 bacteriophage.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Chalcogel is an aerogel made of chalcogens (the column of elements on the periodic table beginning with oxygen) such as sulfur, selenium, and other elements.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Metals less expensive than platinum have been used in its creation.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogels made of cadmium selenide quantum dots in a porous 3-D network have been developed for use in the semiconductor industry.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogel performance may be augmented for a specific application by the addition of dopants, reinforcing structures, and hybridizing compounds.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] For example, Spaceloft is a composite of aerogel with some kind of fibrous batting.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Amyloid fibrils from food waste (whey) have the potential for use in AF aerogels for gold extraction from e-waste.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Their use would have a less environmental impact than that of the conventional use of activated carbon as adsorbent.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Aerogels are used in a wide range of applications because of their low density, low thermal conductivity, and high surface area.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Silica aerogels were the first to be developed commercially and remain the most widely used type.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Flexible polymer-based aerogels have been developed to overcome the brittleness of traditional silica aerogels and enable thin, mechanically compliant insulating materials for aerospace and electronic systems.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Polyimide aerogel films derived from NASA-developed aerogel technology have been commercialized for such applications; examples include the polyimide aerogel film *AeroZero*.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Silica-based aerogels are not known to be carcinogenic or toxic.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] However, they are a mechanical irritant to the eyes, skin, respiratory tract, and digestive system.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] They can also induce dryness of the skin, eyes, and mucous membranes.
[src:capacitor/aerogel] Therefore, it is recommended that protective gear including respiratory protection, gloves and eye goggles be worn whenever handling or processing bare aerogels, particularly when a dust or fine fragments may occur.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] An **airbag** or **supplemental inflatable restraint** is a vehicle occupant-restraint system using a bag designed to inflate in milliseconds during a collision and then deflate afterwards.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] It consists of an airbag cushion, a flexible fabric bag, an inflation module, and an impact sensor.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The purpose of the airbag is to provide a vehicle occupant with soft cushioning and restraint during a collision.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] It can reduce injuries between the flailing occupant and the vehicle's interior.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The airbag provides an energy-absorbing surface between the vehicle's occupants and a steering wheel, instrument panel, body pillar, headliner, and windshield.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Modern vehicles may contain up to ten airbag modules in various configurations, including driver, passenger, side-curtain, seat-mounted, door-mounted, B- and C-pillar mounted side-impact, knee bolster, inflatable seat belt, and pedestrian airbag modules.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] During a crash, the vehicle's crash sensors provide crucial information to the airbag electronic controller unit (ECU), including collision type, angle, and severity of impact.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Using this information, the airbag ECU's crash algorithm determines if the crash event meets the criteria for deployment and triggers various firing circuits to deploy one or more airbag modules within the vehicle.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Airbag module deployments are activated through a pyrotechnic process designed to be used once as a supplemental restraint system for the vehicle's seat belt systems.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Newer side-impact airbag modules consist of compressed-air cylinders that are triggered in the event of a side-on vehicle impact.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The first commercial designs were introduced in passenger automobiles during the 1970s.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] These designs saw limited success and caused some fatalities.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Broad commercial adoption of airbags occurred in many markets during the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Airbags are considered "passive" restraints and act as a supplement to "active" restraints.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Because no action by a vehicle occupant is required to activate or use the airbag, it is considered a "passive" device.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] This is in contrast to seat belts, which are considered "active" devices because the vehicle occupant must act to enable them.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] This terminology is not related to active and passive safety, which are, respectively, systems designed to prevent collisions in the first place, and systems designed to minimize the effects of collisions once they occur.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In this use, a car Anti-lock braking system qualifies as an active-safety device, while both its seat belts and airbags qualify as passive-safety devices.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Terminological confusion can arise from the fact that passive devices and systems—those requiring no input or action by the vehicle occupant—can operate independently in an active manner; an airbag is one such device.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Vehicle safety professionals are generally careful in their use of language to avoid this sort of confusion.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] However, advertising principles sometimes prevent such semantic caution in the consumer marketing of safety features.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Further confusing the terminology, the aviation safety community uses the terms "active" and "passive" in the *opposite* sense from the automotive industry.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The airbag "for the covering of aeroplane and other vehicle parts" traces its origins to a United States patent, submitted in 1919 by two dentists from Birmingham, Arthur Parrott and Harold Round.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Air-filled bladders were in use as early as 1951.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The airbag specifically for automobile use is credited independently to the American John W.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Hetrick, who filed for an airbag patent on 5 August 1952, that was granted #2,649,311 by the United States Patent Office on 18 August 1953.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] German patent #896,312 filed for by engineer Walter Linderer on 6 October 1951 was issued on 12 November 1953, approximately three months after American John Hetrick.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The airbags proposed by Hetrick and Linderer were based on compressed air released by a spring, bumper contact, or by the driver.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Later research during the 1960s showed that compressed air could not inflate the mechanical airbags fast enough to ensure maximum safety, leading to the current chemical and electrical airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In patent applications, manufacturers sometimes use the term "inflatable occupant restraint systems".
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Hetrick was an industrial engineer and member of the United States Navy.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] His airbag design, however, only came about when he combined his experiences working with navy torpedoes with his desire to protect his family on the road.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Despite working with the major automobile manufacturers of his time, Hetrick was unable to attract investment.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Although airbags are now required in every automobile sold in the United States, Hetrick's 1951 patent filing serves as an example of a "valuable" invention with little economic value to its inventor.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Its first commercial use was not implemented until after the patent expired in 1971, at which point the airbag was installed in a few experimental Ford cars.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1964, a Japanese automobile engineer, Yasuzaburou Kobori (小堀保三郎), started developing an airbag "safety net" system.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] His design harnessed an explosive to inflate an airbag, for which he was later awarded patents in 14 countries.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] He died in 1975, before seeing the widespread adoption of airbag systems.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1967, a breakthrough in developing airbag crash sensors came when Allen K.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Breed invented a ball-in-tube mechanism for crash detection.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Under his system, an electromechanical sensor with a steel ball attached to a tube by a magnet would inflate an airbag in under 30 milliseconds.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] A small explosion of sodium azide was used instead of compressed air during inflation for the first time.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Breed Corporation then marketed this innovation to Chrysler.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] A similar "Auto-Ceptor" crash-restraint, developed by the Eaton, Yale & Towne company for Ford, was soon also offered as an automatic safety system in the United States, while the Italian Eaton-Livia company offered a variant with localized air cushions.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In the early 1970s, General Motors began offering cars equipped with airbags, initially in government fleet-purchased 1973 Chevrolet Impala sedans.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] These cars came with a 1974-style Oldsmobile instrument panel and a unique steering wheel that contained the driver-side airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Two of these cars were crash tested after 20 years and the airbags deployed perfectly.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] An early example of the airbag cars survives as of 2009.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] GM's Oldsmobile Toronado was the first domestic U.S. vehicle to include a passenger airbag in 1973.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] General Motors marketed its first airbag modules under the "Air Cushion Restraint System" name, or ACRS.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The automaker discontinued the option for its 1977 model year, citing a lack of consumer interest.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Ford and GM then spent years lobbying against air-bag requirements, claiming that the devices were unfeasible and inappropriate.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Chrysler made driver-side airbags standard on 1988 and 1989 models, but airbags did not become widespread in American cars until the early 1990s.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Airbags for passenger cars were introduced in the United States in the 1970s.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] When seat-belt usage rates in the country were quite low compared to modern-day, Ford built experimental cars with airbags in 1971.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Allstate operated a fleet of 200 Mercury Montereys and showed the reliability of airbags as well as their operation in crash testing, which also was promoted by the insurance company in popular magazine advertisements.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] General Motors followed in 1973 using full-sized Chevrolet vehicles.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The early fleet of experimental GM vehicles equipped with airbags experienced seven fatalities, one of which was later suspected to have been caused by the airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1974, GM made its ACRS system (which consisted of a padded lower dashboard and a passenger-side air bag) available as a regular production option (RPO code AR3) in full-sized Cadillac, Buick and Oldsmobile models.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The GM cars from the 1970s equipped with ACRS had a driver-side airbag, and a driver-side knee restraint.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The passenger-side airbag protected both front passengers, and unlike most modern systems, integrated a knee and torso cushion while also having a dual-stage deployment dictated by force of the impact.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The cars equipped with ACRS had lap belts for all seating positions, but lacked shoulder belts.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Shoulder belts were already mandatory in the United States on closed cars without airbags for the driver and outer front passenger, but GM chose to market its airbags as a substitute for shoulder belts.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The early development of airbags coincided with international interest in automobile safety legislation.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Some safety experts advocated a performance-based occupant-protection standard rather than one mandating a particular technical solution (which could rapidly become outdated and prove to not be a cost-effective approach).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Less emphasis was placed on other designs as countries successfully mandated seat belt restrictions, however.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The auto industry and research and regulatory communities have moved away from their initial view of the airbag as a seat-belt replacement, and the bags are now nominally designated as **supplemental restraint systems** (**SRS**) or supplemental inflatable restraints.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1981, Mercedes-Benz introduced the airbag in West Germany as an option on its flagship saloon model, S-Class (W126).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In the Mercedes system, the sensors automatically tensioned the seat belts to reduce occupants' motion on impact and then deployed the airbag on impact.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] This integrated the seat belts and the airbag into a restraint system, rather than the airbag being considered an alternative to the seat belt.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1987, the Porsche 944 Turbo became the first car to have driver and passenger airbags as standard equipment.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The Porsche 944 and 944S had this as an available option.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The same year also had the first airbag in a Japanese car, the Honda Legend.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1988, Chrysler became the first United States automaker to fit a driver-side airbag as standard equipment, which was offered in six different models.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The following year, Chrysler became the first US auto manufacturer to offer driver-side airbags in all its new passenger models.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Chrysler also began featuring the airbags in advertisements showing how the devices had saved lives that helped the public know the value of them and safety became a selling advantage in the late 1980s.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] All versions of the Chrysler minivans came with airbags starting for the 1991 model year.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1993, The Lincoln Motor Company boasted that all vehicles in their model line were equipped with dual airbags, one for the driver's side and another for the passenger's side.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The 1993 Jeep Grand Cherokee became the first SUV to offer a driver-side airbag when it was launched in 1992.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Driver and passenger airbags became standard equipment in all Dodge Intrepid, Eagle Vision, and Chrysler Concorde sedans ahead of any safety regulations.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Early 1993 saw the 4-millionth airbag-equipped Chrysler vehicle roll off the assembly line.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In October 1993, the Dodge Ram became the first pickup truck with a standard driver-side airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The first known collision between two airbag-equipped automobiles took place on 12 March 1990 in Virginia, USA.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] A 1989 Chrysler LeBaron crossed the center line and hit another 1989 Chrysler LeBaron in a head-on collision, causing both driver airbags to deploy.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The drivers suffered only minor injuries despite extensive damage to the vehicles.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The United States Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act of 1991 required passenger cars and light trucks built after 1 September 1998 to have airbags for the driver and the front passenger.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In the United States, NHTSA estimated that airbags had saved over 4,600 lives by 1 September 1999; however, the crash deployment experience of the early 1990s installations indicated that some fatalities and serious injuries were in fact caused by airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1998, NHTSA initiated new rules for advanced airbags that gave automakers more flexibility in devising effective technological solutions.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The revised rules also required improved protection for occupants of different sizes regardless of whether they use seat belts, while minimizing the risk to infants, children, and other occupants caused by airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In Europe, airbags were almost unheard of until the early 1990s.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Citroën, Fiat, Nissan, Hyundai, Peugeot, Renault, and Volkswagen followed shortly afterwards.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] By 1999, finding a new mass-market car without an airbag at least as optional equipment was difficult, and some late 1990s products, such as the Volkswagen Golf Mk4, also featured side airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The Peugeot 306 is one example of the European automotive mass-market evolution: starting in early 1993, most of these models did not even offer a driver's airbag as an option, but by 1999, even side airbags were available on several variants.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Audi was late to offer airbag systems on a broader scale, since even in the 1994 model year, its popular models did not offer airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Instead, the German automaker until then relied solely on its proprietary cable-based procon-ten restraint system.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Variable force-deployment front airbags were developed to help minimize injury from the airbag itself.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Many new cars in Latin America, including the Kia Rio, Kia Picanto, Hyundai Grand i10, Mazda 2, Chevrolet Spark and the Chevrolet Onix, are often sold without airbags, as neither airbags nor automatic braking systems in new cars are compulsory in many Latin American countries.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Some require the installation of a minimum of only two airbags in new cars which many in this market have.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The Citroën C4 provided the first "shaped" driver airbag, made possible by this car's unusual fixed-hub steering wheel.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 2019, Honda announced it would introduce a new front passenger airbag technology.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Developed by Autoliv and Honda R&D in Ohio, United States, this new airbag design features three inflatable chambers connected across the front by a "noninflatable sail panel." The two outer chambers are larger than the middle chamber.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] When the airbag deploys, the sail panel cushions the occupant's head from the impact of hitting the airbag, and the three chambers hold the occupant's head in place, like a catcher's mitt.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The goal of the tri-chamber airbag is to help "arrest high-speed movement" of the head, thereby reducing the likelihood of concussion injuries in a collision.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The first vehicle to come with the tri-chamber airbag installed from the factory was in 2020 (for the 2021 model year) for the Acura TLX.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Honda hopes that the new technology will soon make its way to all vehicles.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Mercedes began offering rear passengers protection in frontal collisions in September 2020 (for the 2021 model year) for the Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W223).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The W223 S-Class is the first car equipped with rear seat airbags that use gas to inflate supporting structures that unfold and extend a bag that fills with ambient air, instead of conventional fully gas-inflated airbags that are widely used in automotive airbag systems.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Essentially, two types of side airbags are commonly used today - the side-torso airbag and the side-curtain airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] More recently, center airbags are becoming more common in the European market.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Most vehicles equipped with side-curtain airbags also include side-torso airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] However, some, such as the Chevrolet Cobalt, 2007–09 model Chevrolet Silverado/GMC Sierra, and 2009–12 Dodge Ram do not feature the side-torso airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] From around 2000, side-impact airbags became commonplace on even low- to mid-range vehicles, such as the smaller-engined versions of the Ford Fiesta and Peugeot 206, and curtain airbags were also becoming regular features on mass-market cars.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The Toyota Avensis, launched in 2003, was the first mass-market car to be sold in Europe with nine airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Side-impact airbags or side-torso airbags are a category of airbags usually located in the seat or door panel, and inflate between the seat occupant and the door.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] These airbags are designed to reduce the risk of injury to the pelvic and lower abdomen regions.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Most vehicles are now being equipped with different types of designs, to help reduce injury and ejection from the vehicle in rollover crashes.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] More recent side-airbag designs include a two-chamber system; a firmer lower chamber for the pelvic region and softer upper chamber for the ribcage.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Swedish company Autoliv AB was granted a patent on side-impact airbags, and they were first offered as an option in 1994 on the 1995 Volvo 850, and as standard equipment on all Volvo cars made after 1995.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1997, Saab introduced the first combined head and torso airbags with the launch of the Saab 9-5.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Some cars, such as the 2010 Volkswagen Polo Mk.5 have combined head- and torso-side airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] These are fitted in the backrest of the front seats and protect the head and the torso.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1997, the BMW 7 Series and 5 Series were fitted with tubular-shaped head side airbags (inflatable tubular structure), the "Head Protection System (HPS)" as standard equipment.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] This airbag was designed to offer head protection in side impact collisions and also maintained inflation for up to seven seconds for rollover protection.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] However, this tubular-shaped airbag design has been quickly replaced by an inflatable 'curtain' airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In May 1998, Toyota began offering a side-curtain airbag deploying from the roof on the Progrés.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1998, the Volvo S80 was given roof-mounted curtain airbags to protect both front and rear passengers.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Curtain airbags were then made standard equipment on all new Volvo cars from 2000 except for the first-generation C70, which received an enlarged side-torso airbag that also protects the head of front-seat occupants.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The second-generation C70 convertible received the world's first door-mounted, side-curtain airbags that deployed upwards.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Curtain airbags have been said to reduce brain injury or fatalities by up to 45% in a side impact with an SUV.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] These airbags come in various forms (e.g., tubular, curtain, door-mounted) depending on the needs of the application.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Many recent SUVs and MPVs have a long inflatable curtain airbag that protects all rows of seats.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In many vehicles, the curtain airbags are programmed to deploy during some/all frontal impacts to manage passenger kinetics (e.g. head hitting B-pillar on the rebound), especially in offset crashes such as the IIHS's small overlap crash test.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Roll-sensing curtain airbags are designed to stay inflated for a longer duration of time, cover a larger proportion of the window, and be deployed in a roll-over crash.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] They offer protection to occupants' heads and help to prevent ejection.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] SUVs and pickups are more likely to be equipped with RSCAs due to their higher probability of rolling over and often a switch can disable the feature in case the driver wants to take the vehicle off-road.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 2009, Toyota developed the first production rear-seat center airbag designed to reduce the severity of secondary injuries to rear passengers in a side collision.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] This system deploys from the rear center seat first appearing in on the Crown Majesta.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In late 2012, General Motors with supplier Takata introduced a front center airbag; it deploys from the driver's seat.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Hyundai Motor Group announced its development of a center-side airbag on September 18, 2019, installed inside the driver's seat.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Some Volkswagen vehicles in 2022 equipped with center airbags include the ID.3 and the Golf.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The Polestar 2 also includes a center airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Škoda makes center airbags standard equipment in cars and Honda wants to add center airbags to their advanced airbag system in 2023.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] With EuroNCAP updating its testing guidelines in 2020, European and Australian market vehicles increasingly use front-center airbags, rear torso airbags, and rear seat belt pre-tensioners.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The second driver-side and separate knee airbag was used in the Kia Sportage SUV and has been standard equipment since then.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The airbag is located beneath the steering wheel.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The Toyota Caldina introduced the first driver-side SRS knee airbag on the Japanese market in 2002.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Toyota Avensis became the first vehicle sold in Europe equipped with a driver's knee airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The EuroNCAP reported on the 2003 Avensis, "There has been much effort to protect the driver's knees and legs and a knee airbag worked well." Since then certain models have also included front-passenger knee airbags, which deploy near or over the glove compartment in a crash.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Knee airbags are designed to reduce leg injury.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The knee airbag has become increasingly common since 2000.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 2008, the new Toyota iQ microcar featured the first production rear-curtain shield airbag to protect the rear occupants' heads in the event of a rear-end impact.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Another feature of the Toyota iQ was a seat-cushion airbag in the passenger seat to prevent the pelvis from diving below the lap belt during a frontal impact or submarining.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Later Toyota models such as the Yaris added the feature to the driver's seat, as well.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The seat-belt airbag is designed to better distribute the forces experienced by a buckled person in a crash using an increased seat belt area.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] This is done to reduce possible injuries to the rib cage or chest of the belt wearer.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Cessna Aircraft also introduced seat belt airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Airbag(s) mounted to the exterior of vehicles, so-called "pedestrian airbags", are designed to reduce injuries in the event of a vehicle to a pedestrian collision.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] When a collision is detected the airbag will deploy and cover hard areas, such as a-pillars and bonnet edges, before they can be struck by the pedestrian.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] When introduced in 2012 the Volvo V40 included the world's first pedestrian airbag as standard.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] As a result, the V40 ranked highest (88%) in the EuroNCAP's pedestrian tests.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Suppliers of SRS airbags include Autoliv, Daicel, TRW, and JSS (which owns Breed, Key Safety Systems, and Takata).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The majority of impact sensors of airbags are manufactured by the Lanka Harness Company in Sri Lanka.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The airbags in the vehicle are controlled by a central airbag control unit (ACU), a specific type of ECU.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The ACU monitors several related sensors within the vehicle, including accelerometers, impact sensors, side (door) pressure sensors, wheel speed sensors, gyroscopes, brake pressure sensors, and seat occupancy sensors.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Oftentimes, ACUs log this—and other—sensor data in a circular buffer and record it to onboard non-volatile memory, to provide a snapshot of the crash event for investigators.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] As such, an ACU frequently functions as the vehicle's event data recorder (EDR); not all EDRs are ACUs, and not all ACUs include EDR features.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] An ACU typically includes capacitors within its circuitry, so that the module remains powered and able to deploy the airbags if the vehicle's battery connection to the ACU is severed during a crash.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The bag itself and its inflation mechanism are concealed within the steering wheel boss (for the driver), or the dashboard (for the front passenger), behind plastic flaps or doors that are designed to tear open under the force of the bag inflating.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Once the requisite threshold has been reached or exceeded, the airbag control unit will trigger the ignition of a gas generator propellant to rapidly inflate a fabric bag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] As the vehicle occupant collides with and squeezes the bag, the gas escapes in a controlled manner through small vent holes.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The airbag's volume and the size of the vents in the bag are tailored to each vehicle type, to spread out the deceleration of (and thus force experienced by) the occupant over time and over the occupant's body, compared to a seat belt alone.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The signals from the various sensors are fed into the airbag control unit, which determines from them the angle of impact, the severity, or the force of the crash, along with other variables.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Depending on the result of these calculations, the ACU may also deploy various additional restraint devices, such as seat belt pre-tensioners, and/or airbags (including frontal bags for driver and front passenger, along with seat-mounted side bags, and "curtain" airbags which cover the side glass).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Each restraint device is typically activated with one or more pyrotechnic devices, commonly called an initiator or electric match.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The electric match, which consists of an electrical conductor wrapped in a combustible material, activates with a current pulse between 1 and 3 amps in less than 2 milliseconds.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] When the conductor becomes hot enough, it ignites the combustible material, which initiates the gas generator.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In a seat belt pre-tensioner, this hot gas is used to drive a piston that pulls the slack out of the seat belt.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In an airbag, the initiator is used to ignite solid propellant inside the airbag inflator.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The burning propellant generates inert gas which rapidly inflates the airbag in approximately 20 to 30 ms.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] An airbag must inflate quickly to be fully inflated by the time the forward-traveling occupant reaches its outer surface.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Typically, the decision to deploy an airbag in a frontal crash is made within 15 to 30 ms after the onset of the crash, and both the driver and passenger airbags are fully inflated within approximately 60 to 80 ms after the first moment of vehicle contact.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] If an airbag deploys too late or too slowly, the risk of occupant injury from contact with the inflating airbag may increase.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Since more distance typically exists between the passenger and the instrument panel, the passenger airbag is larger and requires more gas to fill it.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Older airbag systems contained a mixture of sodium azide (NaN3), KNO3, and SiO2.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] A typical driver-side airbag contains approximately 50–80 grams (1.8–2.8 oz) of NaN3, with the larger passenger-side airbag containing about 250 grams (8.8 oz).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Within about 40 milliseconds of impact, all these components react in three separate reactions that produce nitrogen gas.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The reactions, in order, are as follows.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The first two reactions create 4 molar equivalents of nitrogen gas, and the third converts the remaining reactants to relatively inert potassium silicate and sodium silicate.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] There are ongoing efforts to find alternative compounds so that airbags have less toxic reactants.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The reaction of the Sr complex nitrate, (SrOC(N2H3)2·(NO3)2) of carbohydrazide (SrCDH) with various oxidizing agents results in the evolution of N2 and CO2 gases.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The N2 and CO2 gases evolved made up 99% of all gases evolved.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Nearly all of the starting materials will not decompose until reaching temperatures of 500 °C (932 °F) or higher, so this could be a viable option as an airbag gas generator.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Since airbags deploy only once and deflate quickly after the initial impact, they will not be beneficial during a subsequent collision.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In vehicles equipped with a rollover sensing system, accelerometers, and gyroscopes are used to sense the onset of a rollover event.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] If a rollover event is determined to be imminent, side-curtain airbags are deployed to help protect the occupant from contact with the side of the vehicle interior, and also to help prevent occupant ejection as the vehicle rolls over.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] International regulations are performance-based, rather than technology-based, so airbag deployment threshold is a function of overall vehicle design.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Unlike crash tests into barriers, real-world crashes typically occur at angles other than directly into the front of the vehicle, and the crash forces usually are not evenly distributed across the front of the vehicle.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Consequently, the relative speed between a striking and struck vehicle required to deploy the airbag in a real-world crash can be much higher than an equivalent barrier crash.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Because airbag sensors measure deceleration, the vehicle speed is not a good indicator of whether an airbag should be deployed.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Airbags can deploy due to the vehicle's undercarriage striking a low object protruding above the roadway due to the resulting deceleration.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The airbag sensor is a MEMS accelerometer, which is a small integrated circuit with integrated micromechanical elements.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The microscopic mechanical element moves in response to rapid deceleration, and this motion causes a change in capacitance, which is detected by the electronics on the chip that then sends a signal to fire the airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The most common MEMS accelerometer in use is the ADXL-50 by Analog Devices, but there are other MEMS manufacturers as well.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Initial attempts using mercury switches did not work well.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Before MEMS, the primary system used to deploy airbags was called a "rolamite".
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] A rolamite is a mechanical device, consisting of a roller suspended within a tensioned band.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] As a result of the particular geometry and material properties used, the roller is free to translate with little friction or hysteresis.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] This device was developed at Sandia National Laboratories.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Rolamite and similar macro-mechanical devices were used in airbags until the mid-1990s after which they were universally replaced with MEMS.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Nearly all airbags are designed to automatically deploy in the event of a vehicle fire when temperatures reach 150–200 °C (302–392 °F).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] This safety feature, often termed auto-ignition, helps to ensure that such temperatures do not cause an explosion of the entire airbag module.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Today, airbag triggering algorithms are much more complex, being able to adapt the deployment speed to the crash conditions, and prevent unnecessary deployments.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The algorithms are considered valuable intellectual property.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Experimental algorithms may take into account such factors as the weight of the occupant, the seat location, and seat belt use, as well as even attempt to determine if a baby seat is present.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] When the frontal airbags are to deploy, a signal is sent to the gas generator/inflator unit within the airbag control unit.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] An igniter starts a rapid chemical reaction generating primarily nitrogen gas (N2) to fill the airbag making it deploy through the module cover.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Some airbag technologies use compressed nitrogen or argon gas with a pyrotechnic operated valve ("hybrid gas generator"), while other technologies use various energetic propellants.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Although propellants containing the highly toxic sodium azide (NaN3) were common in early inflator designs, little to no toxic sodium azide has been found on used airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The azide-containing pyrotechnic gas generators contain a substantial amount of the propellant.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The driver-side airbag would contain a canister containing about 50 grams (1.8 oz) of sodium azide.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The passenger side container holds about 200 grams (7.1 oz) of sodium azide.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] From the onset of the crash, the entire deployment and inflation process is about 0.04 seconds.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Because vehicles change speed so quickly in a crash, airbags must inflate rapidly to reduce the risk of the occupant hitting the vehicle's interior.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Advanced airbag technologies are being developed to tailor airbag deployment to the severity of the crash, the size, and posture of the vehicle occupant, belt usage, and how close that person is to the actual airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Many of these systems use multi-stage inflators that deploy less forcefully in stages in moderate crashes than in very severe crashes.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Occupant sensing devices let the airbag control unit know if someone is occupying a seat adjacent to an airbag, the mass/weight of the person, whether a seat belt or child restraint is being used, and whether the person is forward in the seat and close to the airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Based on this information and crash severity information, the airbag is deployed at either a high force level, a less forceful level, or not at all.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Adaptive airbag systems may utilize multi-stage airbags to adjust the pressure within the airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The greater the pressure within the airbag, the more force the airbag will exert on the occupants as they come in contact with it.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] These adjustments allow the system to deploy the airbag with a moderate force for most collisions; reserving the maximum force airbag only for the severest of collisions.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Additional sensors to determine the location, weight or relative size of the occupants may also be used.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Information regarding the occupants and the severity of the crash are used by the airbag control unit, to determine whether airbags should be suppressed or deployed, and if so, at various output levels.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] A chemical reaction produces a burst of nitrogen to inflate the bag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Once an airbag deploys, deflation begins immediately as the gas escapes through vent(s) in the fabric (or, as it is sometimes called, the cushion) and cools.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Deployment is frequently accompanied by the release of dust-like particles, and gases in the vehicle's interior (called effluent).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Most of this dust consists of cornstarch, french chalk, or talcum powder, which are used to lubricate the airbag during deployment.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Newer designs produce effluent primarily consisting of harmless talcum powder/cornstarch and nitrogen gas.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In older designs using an azide-based propellant (usually NaN3), varying amounts of sodium hydroxide nearly always are initially present.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In small amounts this chemical can cause minor irritation to the eyes and/or open wounds; however, with exposure to air, it quickly turns into sodium bicarbonate (baking soda).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] However, this transformation is not 100% complete, and invariably leaves residual amounts of hydroxide ions from NaOH.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Depending on the type of airbag system, potassium chloride may also be present.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] For most people, the only effect the dust may produce is some minor irritation of the throat and eyes.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Generally, minor irritations only occur when the occupant remains in the vehicle for many minutes with the windows closed and no ventilation.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] However, some people with asthma may develop a potentially lethal asthmatic attack from inhaling the dust.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Because of the airbag exit flap design of the steering wheel boss and dashboard panel, these items are not designed to be recoverable if an airbag deploys, meaning that they have to be replaced if the vehicle has not been written off in a collision.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Moreover, the dust-like particles and gases can cause irreparable cosmetic damage to the dashboard and upholstery, meaning that minor collisions that result in the deployment of airbags can be costly, even if there are no injuries and there is only minor damage to the vehicle structure.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] On 11 July 1984, the United States government amended Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 208 (FMVSS 208) to require cars produced after 1 April 1989 to be equipped with a passive restraint for the driver.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] An airbag or an automatic seat belt would meet the requirements of the standard.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Airbag introduction was stimulated by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] However, airbags were not mandatory on light trucks until 1997.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 1998, FMVSS 208 was amended to require dual front airbags, and reduced-power, second-generation airbags were also mandated.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] This was due to the injuries caused by first-generation airbags, though FMVSS 208 continues to require that bags be engineered and calibrated to be able to "save" the life of an *unbelted* 50th-percentile size and weight "male" crash test dummy.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The technical performance and validation requirements for the inflator assembly used in airbag modules are specified in SAE USCAR 24–2.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Some countries outside North America adhere to internationalized European ECE vehicle and equipment regulations rather than the United States Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] ECE airbags are generally smaller and inflate less forcefully than United States airbags because the ECE specifications are based on *belted* crash test dummies.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The Euro NCAP vehicle safety rating encourages manufacturers to take a comprehensive approach to occupant safety; a good rating can only be achieved by combining airbags with other safety features.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Almost every new car sold in Europe is equipped with front and side airbags, but in the European Union in 2020 and in the United Kingdom, and most other developed countries there is no direct legal requirement for new cars to feature airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Ecuador requires dual front airbags in new car models since 2013.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Since January 2014, except for micro vehicles, all new cars made or imported in Argentina must have front airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Since 1 January 2014, all new cars sold in Brazil must have dual front airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Since July 2014, all new cars sold in Uruguay must have dual front airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Since December 2016, all new cars sold in Chile must have dual front airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Since 1 January 2017, all cars made or imported in Colombia must have dual front airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Since 1 January 2020, all new cars sold in Mexico must have dual front airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] On 5 March 2021, the Indian Ministry of Road Transport and Highways mandated that all new vehicle models introduced in India after 1 April 2021 have dual front airbags; the regulation also requires that all existing models be equipped with dual front airbags by 31 August 2021.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] India also mandated that all passenger vehicles sold after October 2023 must have a minimum of six airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Inadvertent airbag deployment while a vehicle is being serviced can result in serious injury, and an improperly installed or defective airbag unit may fail to operate as intended.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] For this reason, individuals servicing vehicles, as well as first responders, are required to account for the fact that some airbag control systems may remain powered for up to 30 minutes after a vehicle's battery has been disconnected.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In some countries, the sale, transport, handling, and servicing of airbags and related components are subject to legal restrictions.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In Germany, for example, airbags are regulated as hazardous explosive devices, and only trained auto mechanics are permitted to service airbag systems.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Automaker policies regarding the service life of undeployed airbags vary.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Some manufacturers, such as Mercedes-Benz, have historically recommended replacement after a specified period to ensure reliability.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Certain Škoda vehicles have indicated an airbag service life of approximately 14 years from the date of manufacture, after which replacement may be uneconomical relative to the vehicle’s value.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] By contrast, Volvo has stated that airbags are designed to last for the lifetime of the vehicle, although this is not presented as an absolute guarantee of performance.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Although the millions of installed airbags in use have an excellent safety record, some limitations on their ability to protect car occupants exist.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The original implementation of front airbags did little to protect against side collisions, which can be more dangerous than frontal collisions because the protective crumple zone in front of the passenger compartment is completely bypassed.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Side airbags and protective airbag curtains are increasingly being required in modern vehicles to protect against this very common category of collisions.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Airbags are designed to deploy once only, so are ineffective if any further collisions occur after an initial impact.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Multiple impacts may occur during rollovers or other incidents involving multiple collisions, such as many multivehicle collisions.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] An extremely dangerous situation occurs during "underride collisions", in which a passenger vehicle collides with the rear of a tractor-trailer lacking a rear underride guard, or hits the side of such a trailer not equipped with a side underride guard.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] The platform bed of a typical trailer is roughly at the head height of a seated adult occupant of a typical passenger car.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] This means not much of a barrier exists between a head and the edge of the trailer platform, except a glass windshield.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In an underride collision, the car's crush zones designed to absorb collision energy are completely bypassed, and the airbags may not deploy in time because the car does not decelerate appreciably until the windshield and roof pillars have already impacted the trailer bed.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Even delayed inflation of airbags may be useless because of major intrusion into the passenger space, leaving occupants at high risk of major head trauma or decapitation in even low-speed collisions.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Western European standards for underride guards have been stricter than North American standards, which typically have allowed grandfathering of older equipment that may still be on the road for decades.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Typical airbag systems are completely disabled by turning off the ignition key.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Unexpected turnoffs usually also disable the engine, power steering, and power brakes, and can be the direct cause of a collision.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] If a violent collision occurs, the disabled airbags will not deploy to protect vehicle occupants.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] In 2014, General Motors admitted to concealing information about fatal collisions caused by defective ignition switches that would abruptly shut down a car (including its airbags).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p01] Between 13 and 74 deaths have been directly attributed to this defect, depending on how the fatalities are classified.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Under some rare conditions, airbags can injure and in some very rare instances kill vehicle occupants.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] To provide crash protection for occupants not wearing seat belts, United States airbag designs trigger much more forcefully than airbags designed to the international ECE standards used in most other countries.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Recent "smart" airbag controllers can recognize if a seat belt is used, and alter the airbag cushion deployment parameters accordingly.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] In 1990, the first automotive fatality attributed to an airbag was reported.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] TRW produced the first gas-inflated airbag in 1994, with sensors and low inflation-force bags becoming common soon afterward.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Dual-depth (also known as dual-stage) airbags appeared on passenger cars in 1998.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] By 2005, deaths related to airbags had declined, with no adult deaths and two child deaths attributed to airbags that year.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] However, injuries remain fairly common in collisions with airbag deployment.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Serious injuries are less common, but severe or fatal injuries can occur to vehicle occupants very near an airbag or in direct contact when it deploys.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Such injuries may be sustained by unconscious drivers slumped over the steering wheel, unrestrained or improperly restrained occupants who slide forward in the seat during precrash braking, and properly belted drivers sitting very close to the steering wheel.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] A US study showed that the risk for a serious head injury occurring is 5.495% while travelling 40–48 km/h (25–30 mph).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The risk is reduced for passengers to 4.435%.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] This risk is lowered by 80.5% to 1.073% when using an airbag.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The risk for passengers is lowered by 82% to 0.797%.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The tests with the airbags were done at 56 km/h (35 mph), 8–16 km/h (5–10 mph) faster than the tests without air bags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] There is a 15.45% risk of serious injury to unprotected occupants at 48–56 km/h (30–35 mph), this drops to 4.68% with protected occupants.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] This is a 69.7% decrease in change of serious injury, with the airbags deploying 96.1% of the time.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Improvements in sensing and gas-generator technology have allowed the development of third-generation airbag systems that can adjust their deployment parameters to the size, weight, position, and restraint status of the occupant.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] These improvements have demonstrated a reduced injury risk factor for small adults and children, who had an increased risk of injury with first-generation airbag systems.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] One model of airbags made by the Takata Corporation used ammonium nitrate–based gas-generating compositions in airbag inflators instead of the more stable, but more expensive compound tetrazole.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The ammonium nitrate-based inflators have a flaw where old inflators with long-term exposure to hot and humid climate conditions could rupture during deployment, projecting metal shards through the airbag and into the driver.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] As of December 2022, the defect has caused 33 deaths worldwide, with up to 24 in the U.S. and the remaining in Australia and Malaysia.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) recalled over 33 million vehicles in May 2015, and fined Takata $70 million in November 2015.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Toyota, Mazda, and Honda have said that they will not use ammonium-nitrate inflators.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] In June 2017, Takata filed for bankruptcy.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] From 1990 to 2000, the United States NHTSA identified 175 fatalities caused by airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] About 3.3 million airbag deployments have occurred during that interval, and the agency estimates more than 6,377 lives were saved and countless injuries were prevented.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] A rear-facing infant restraint put in the front seat of a vehicle places an infant's head close to the airbag, which can cause severe head injuries or death if the airbag deploys.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Some modern cars include a switch to disable the front-passenger airbag, in case a child-supporting seat is used there (although not in Australia, where rear-facing child seats are prohibited in the front where an airbag is fitted).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] In vehicles with side airbags, it is dangerous for occupants to lean against the windows, doors, and pillars, or to place objects between themselves and the side of the vehicle.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Articles hung from a vehicle's clothes hanger hooks can be hazardous if the vehicle's side-curtain airbags are deployed.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] A seat-mounted airbag may also cause internal injury if the occupant leans against the door.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The aerospace industry and the United States government have applied airbag technologies for many years.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] NASA and United States Department of Defense have incorporated airbag systems in various aircraft and spacecraft applications as early as the 1960s.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The first use of airbags for landing were Luna 9 and Luna 13.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] As with later missions, these would use the airbags to bounce along the surface, absorbing landing energy.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The Mars Pathfinder lander employed an innovative airbag landing system, supplemented with aerobraking, parachute, and solid rocket landing thrusters.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] This prototype successfully tested the concept, and the two Mars Exploration Rover Mission landers employed similar landing systems.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The Beagle 2 Mars lander also tried to use airbags for landing; the landing was successful, and the lander touched down safely, but several of the spacecraft's solar panels failed to deploy, thereby disabling the spacecraft.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The Boeing Starliner uses six airbags to cushion the ground landing of the crewed capsule.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Airbags have also been used on military fixed-wing aircraft, such as the escape crew capsule of the F-111 Aardvark.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The United States Army has incorporated airbags in its UH-60A/L Black Hawk and OH-58D Kiowa Warrior helicopter fleets.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The Cockpit Air Bag System (CABS) consists of forward and lateral airbags, and an inflatable tubular structure (on the OH-58D only) with an Electronic Crash Sensor Unit (ECSU).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] The CABS system was developed by the United States Army Aviation Applied Technology Directorate, through a contract with Simula Safety Systems (now BAE Systems).
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] It is the first conventional airbag system for occupant injury prevention (worldwide) designed and developed and placed in service for an aircraft, and the first specifically for helicopter applications.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] In the mid-1970s, the UK Transport Research Laboratory tested several types of motorcycle airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] In 2006 Honda introduced the first production motorcycle airbag safety system on its Gold Wing motorcycle.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Honda claims that sensors in the front forks can detect a severe frontal collision and decide when to deploy the airbag, absorbing some of the forward energy of the rider and reducing the velocity at which the rider may be thrown from the motorcycle.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] More commonly, air bag vests – either integrated into the motorcyclist's jacket or worn over it – have started to become used by regular riders on the street.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] MotoGP has made it compulsory since 2018 for riders to wear suits with integrated airbags.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Similarly, companies such as Helite and Hit-Air have commercialized equestrian airbags, which attach to the saddle and are worn by the rider.
[src:capacitor/airbag-p02] Other sports, particularly skiing and snowboarding, have started introducing airbag safety mechanisms.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] A **capacitor** is a device that stores electrical energy by accumulating electric charges on two closely spaced surfaces that are insulated from each other.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] It is a passive electronic component with two terminals.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] A capacitor was originally known as a **condenser**, a term still encountered in a few compound names, such as the *condenser microphone*.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Colloquially, a capacitor may be called a ***cap***.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The utility of a capacitor depends on its capacitance.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] While some capacitance exists between any two electrical conductors in proximity in a circuit, a capacitor is a component designed specifically to add capacitance to some part of the circuit.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The physical form and construction of practical capacitors vary widely and many types of capacitor are in common use.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Most capacitors contain at least two electrical conductors, often in the form of metallic plates or surfaces separated by a dielectric medium.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] A conductor may be a foil, thin film, sintered bead of metal, or an electrolyte.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The nonconducting dielectric acts to increase the capacitor's charge capacity.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Materials commonly used as dielectrics include glass, ceramic, plastic film, paper, mica, air, and oxide layers.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] No current actually flows through a perfect dielectric.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] However, there is a flow of charge through the source circuit.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] If the condition is maintained sufficiently long, the current through the source circuit ceases.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] If a time-varying voltage is applied across the leads of the capacitor, the source experiences an ongoing current due to the charging and discharging cycles of the capacitor.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are widely used as parts of electrical circuits in many common electrical devices.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Unlike a resistor, an ideal capacitor does not dissipate energy, although real-life capacitors do dissipate a small amount .
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The earliest forms of capacitors were created in the 1740s, when European experimenters discovered that electric charge could be stored in water-filled glass jars that came to be known as Leyden jars.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Today, capacitors are widely used in electronic circuits for blocking direct current while allowing alternating current to pass.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] In analog filter networks, they smooth the output of power supplies.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] In resonant circuits they tune radios to particular frequencies.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] In electric power transmission systems, they stabilize voltage and power flow.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The property of energy storage in capacitors was exploited as dynamic memory in early digital computers, and still is in modern DRAM.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The most common example of natural capacitance are the static charges accumulated between clouds in the sky and the surface of the Earth, where the air between them serves as the dielectric.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] This results in bolts of lightning when the breakdown voltage of the air is exceeded.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] In October 1745, Ewald Georg von Kleist of Pomerania, Germany, found that charge could be stored by connecting a high-voltage electrostatic generator by a wire to a volume of water in a hand-held glass jar.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist's hand and the water acted as conductors and the jar as a dielectric (although details of the mechanism were incorrectly identified at the time).
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist found that touching the wire resulted in a powerful spark, much more painful than that obtained from an electrostatic machine.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The following year, the Dutch physicist Pieter van Musschenbroek invented a similar capacitor, which was named the Leyden jar, after the University of Leiden where he worked.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Daniel Gralath was the first to combine several jars in parallel to increase the charge storage capacity.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Benjamin Franklin investigated the Leyden jar and came to the conclusion that the charge was stored on the glass, not in the water as others had assumed.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] He also adopted the term "battery", (denoting the increase of power with a row of similar units as in a battery of cannon), subsequently applied to clusters of electrochemical cells.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] In 1747, Leyden jars were made by coating the inside and outside of jars with metal foil, leaving a space at the mouth to prevent arcing between the foils.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The earliest unit of capacitance was the jar, equivalent to about 1.11 nanofarads.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] More compact construction methods began to be used, such as a flexible dielectric sheet (like oiled paper) sandwiched between sheets of metal foil, rolled or folded into a small package.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Early capacitors were known as *condensers*, a term that is still occasionally used today, particularly in high power applications, such as automotive systems.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The term became deprecated because of the ambiguous meaning of steam condenser, with *capacitor* being recommended by the British Engineering Standards Association in 1926, although it took several decades for the term to predominate.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Since the beginning of the study of electricity, non-conductive materials like glass, porcelain, paper and mica have been used as insulators.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Decades later, these materials were also well-suited for use as the dielectric for the first capacitors.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Paper capacitors, made by sandwiching a strip of impregnated paper between strips of metal and rolling the result into a cylinder, were commonly used in the late 19th century; their manufacture started in 1876, and they were used from the early 20th century as decoupling capacitors in telephony.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Porcelain was used in the first ceramic capacitors.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] In the early years of Marconi's wireless transmitting apparatus, porcelain capacitors were used for high voltage and high frequency application in the transmitters.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] On the receiver side, smaller mica capacitors were used for resonant circuits.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Mica capacitors were invented in 1909 by William Dubilier.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Prior to World War II, mica was the most common dielectric for capacitors in the United States.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Charles Pollak (born Karol Pollak), the inventor of the first electrolytic capacitors, found out that the oxide layer on an aluminum anode remained stable in a neutral or alkaline electrolyte, even when the power was switched off.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] 672,913 for an "Electric liquid capacitor with aluminum electrodes".
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Solid electrolyte tantalum capacitors were invented by Bell Laboratories in the early 1950s as a miniaturized and more reliable low-voltage support capacitor to complement their newly invented transistor.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] With the development of plastic materials by organic chemists during the Second World War, the capacitor industry began to replace paper with thinner polymer films.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] One very early development in film capacitors was described in British Patent 587,953 in 1944.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Electric double-layer capacitors (now supercapacitors) were invented in 1957 when H.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Becker developed a "Low voltage electrolytic capacitor with porous carbon electrodes".
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] He believed that the energy was stored as a charge in the carbon pores used in his capacitor as in the pores of the etched foils of electrolytic capacitors.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The MOS capacitor was later widely adopted as a storage capacitor in memory chips, and as the basic building block of the charge-coupled device (CCD) in image sensor technology.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Robert Dennard invented modern DRAM architecture, combining a single MOS transistor per capacitor.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] A capacitor consists of two conductors separated by a non-conductive region.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The non-conductive region can either be a vacuum or an electrical insulator material known as a dielectric.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Examples of dielectric media are glass, air, paper, plastic, ceramic, and even a semiconductor depletion region chemically identical to the conductors.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] From Coulomb's law, a charge on one conductor will exert a force on the charge carriers within the other conductor, attracting opposite polarity charge and repelling like polarity charges, thus an opposite polarity charge will be induced on the surface of the other conductor.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The conductors thus hold equal and opposite charges on their facing surfaces, and the dielectric develops an electric field.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] A capacitance of one farad (1 F) means that one coulomb of charge on each conductor causes a voltage of one volt across the device.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Because the conductors (or plates) are close together, the opposite charges on the conductors attract one another due to their electric fields, allowing the capacitor to store more charge for a given voltage than when the conductors are separated, yielding a larger capacitance.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] In practical devices, charge build-up sometimes affects the capacitor mechanically, causing its capacitance to vary.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] In the hydraulic analogy, voltage is analogous to water pressure and electrical current through a wire is analogous to water flow through a pipe.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] A capacitor is like an elastic diaphragm within the pipe.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Although water cannot pass through the diaphragm, it moves as the diaphragm stretches or un-stretches.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] In a circuit, a capacitor can behave differently at different time instants.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] The simplest model of a capacitor consists of two thin parallel conductive plates each with an area of A separated by a uniform gap of thickness d filled with a dielectric of permittivity ⁠ $\varepsilon$ ⁠.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] It is assumed the gap d is much smaller than the dimensions of the plates.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] This model applies well to many practical capacitors which are constructed of metal sheets separated by a thin layer of insulating dielectric, since manufacturers try to keep the dielectric very uniform in thickness to avoid thin spots which can cause failure of the capacitor.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] This "fringing field" area is approximately the same width as the plate separation, ⁠ d ⁠, and assuming d is small compared to the plate dimensions, it is small enough to be ignored.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] From Gauss's law the magnitude of the electric field between the plates is ⁠ $\textstyle E={\sigma \over \varepsilon }$ ⁠.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Therefore, in a capacitor the highest capacitance is achieved with a high permittivity dielectric material, large plate area, and small separation between the plates.
[src:capacitor/capacitor-p01] Since the area A of the plates increases with the square of the linear dimensions and the separation d increases linearly, the capacitance scales with the linear dimension of a capacitor (⁠ $C\varpropto L$ ⁠), or as the cube root of the volume.
